\title{Performance considerations}

\p{If one is not careful, certain code can make Agda become very slow
to type check. This is usually due to the normal form of terms becoming
extremely large. We document some strategies we have found to keep Agda
running faster:

\ul{
\li{\strong{[Opaque
blocks](https://agda.readthedocs.io/en/latest/language/opaque-definitions.html)}. By
marking a definition as opaque, Agda will treat it as a black box;
never unfolding the definition.  The one exception to this is inside
an opaque block, before any definitions, you may see through some
other opaque definition by adding a line \code{unfolding
my-opaque-def}. Opaque is the main tool to improve performance, and
can be applied quite liberally without affecting the usability of the
codebase. For example, if you give a term of an identity type, which
you know is subject to no further coherence conditions, and the proof
is involved, then this should almost be marked opaque. An important
place to carefully consider the opacity of a definition is in proofs of
\code{is-equiv ...}. Whilst this is a proposition, and so making it
opaque loses no information, it is sometimes useful to be able to
compute the inverse map; so whether to make such a proof opaque
depends on how it is constructed, and the normal form of the inverse
map.
}
}
